															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/captain-kirby" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3440103); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=3440103&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610175953" alt="Captain Kirby" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=3440103)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/captain-kirby" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3440103); return false;" >Captain Kirby</a></span> <span class="odate time_1604677710 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">06 Nov 2020 15:48</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4812489">
									

<p>I feel like no individual iteration of this proposal properly builds on previous iterations in a meaningful way. Like, it doesn't help that I felt like I was reading file editing logistics, which without any clear stakes is not particularly engaging. There were times that it felt like this was trying to explain site lore just for the sake of expanding lore because I never understood what it had to do with the throughline of the article. The way it loops in other proposals and the heritage collection felt particularly superfluous to the themes of SCP-001 having specific anomalous properties regarding consensus reality (which still felt underdeveloped in context of the scope of this piece).</p>
<p>I get that the last iteration is a language gimmick intended to like, mimic reality destabilizing, but the way that you've decided to just remove the letter &quot;a&quot; entirely just makes it unpleasant to read.</p>
<p>To me there were only 2 moments when I felt like there was some tangible set of stakes/conflict, and that's during the phone call, and the back and forth between the archivist and the primordial. These are definitely the strongest parts of the piece, but neither are expanded upon in a meaningful way to actually carry that investment over across the rest of the article.</p>
<p>By the end of the article, I don't know what I am supposed to be invested in, and if there is a mystery I don't know what questions I am supposed to be asking.</p>
<p>-1</p>

